color <- function(x, color="red") {
  if (knitr::is_latex_output()) {
    sprintf("\\textcolor{%s}{%s}", color, x)
  } else if (knitr::is_html_output()) {
    sprintf("<span style='color: %s;'>%s</span>", color, 
      x)
  } else x
}

#function that displays the OR, CI and p-values from a logistic model
get.OR2<-function(my.mod, names.var=NULL){
  my.coef <- summary(my.mod)$coef
  tmp<-cbind(exp(my.coef[,1]), exp(my.coef[,1]-qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]),  exp(my.coef[,1]+qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]), my.coef[,4])
  dimnames(tmp)[[2]]<-c("OR", "95\\% CI LL",  "95\\% CI UL", "P-value")
  if(!is.null(names.var))   dimnames(tmp)[[1]]<-names.var else dimnames(tmp)[[1]] <- dimnames(my.coef)[[1]]
  tmp
}



#function that displays the OR, CI and p-values from a logistic model, formatted better for the output
get.OR3<-function(my.mod, names.var=NULL, num.digits=2, thr.p=0.01, num.digits.p =2){
  my.coef <- summary(my.mod)$coef
  tmp<-cbind(exp(my.coef[,1]), exp(my.coef[,1]-qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]),  exp(my.coef[,1]+qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]), my.coef[,4])
  dimnames(tmp)[[2]]<-c("OR", "95\\% CI LL",  "95\\% CI UL", "P-value")
  if(!is.null(names.var))   dimnames(tmp)[[1]]<-names.var else dimnames(tmp)[[1]] <- dimnames(my.coef)[[1]]
  tmp
  
  
  

   tmp<-cbind.data.frame(OR=round(exp(my.coef[,1]), digits=num.digits ), 
                         "95\\% CI"=paste0(round(exp(my.coef[,1]-qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]), digits=num.digits),  "-", round(exp(my.coef[,1]+qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]), num.digits)),  
                                       
                                       "P"=ifelse(my.coef[,4]<thr.p, paste0("<", thr.p), round(my.coef[,4], digits=num.digits.p))
   )
                         
  #dimnames(tmp)[[2]]<-c("OR", "95\\% CI LL",  "95\\% CI UL", "P-value")
  if(!is.null(names.var))   dimnames(tmp)[[1]]<-names.var else dimnames(tmp)[[1]] <- dimnames(my.coef)[[1]]
  tmp
  
  
  
}

Statistical methods

The secondary research question is to model each of the 12 items that make up the EURO-D scale as outcomes with the same model(s) for the EURO-D score in Part 2..

1 IDA for the 12 depressive symptoms in EURO-D

Since IDA was already conducted for the explanatory variables in Part 2, here we focus on the 12 outcome variables.

share.data.first.interview %>%

2.2 Model fitting

As in the analysis for EURO-D we fitted types of models to each of 12 depressive symptoms of the EURO-D scale. For cease of comparison the EURO-D models are included first.

  • unadjusted models: including two-way interactions between age, gender and geographic region (unadjusted models)
  • adjusted models: in addition to age, gender, and region as in the unadjusted models further adjusting by known risk factors (education, BMI, smoking, presence of chronic disease, vigorous physical activity, living arrangement)

Age was centered at 50 years and modeled - as a linear effect - as a non-linear effect with restricted cubic splines (rcs) and 5 knots placed at ages: 51, 56, 62, 70 and 81, using the default choice for the quantiles

#definition of standardized age for ease of interpretation of the coefficients
share.data.first.interview<- share.data.first.interview %>% mutate (age_int_stand = age_int - 50)

The country of residence was modeled by grouping the countries into four geographic regions

Some of the coefficients of the estimated model are difficult to interpret, due to the use of restricted cubic splines and of interactions. Therefore, graphical displays of the estimated probabilities are used to present the results, rather than a table with the estimated coefficients. When RCS are used, the estimated coefficients/odds ration (OR) are not presented only age and its interactions.

The models that use age as a linear term are fitted with the aim of evaluating the impact of choice on the estimated results.

i <- 1

share.data.first.interview$y <- share.data.first.interview$euro1

my.mod2 <- glm(y ~ age1 + age2 + age3 + age4 + gender + region + 
                      age1:region + age2:region + age3:region + age4:region +  
                       age1:gender + age2:gender + age3:gender + age4:gender +  
                       gender:region ,
                        data=share.data.first.interview, family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)



my.mod1 <- glm(y ~ rcspline.eval(age_int_stand, knots=Knots, inclx = TRUE)  + gender + region + 
                      rcspline.eval(age_int_stand, knots=Knots, inclx = TRUE):region + 
                       rcspline.eval(age_int_stand, knots=Knots, inclx = TRUE):gender + 
                       gender:region ,
                        data=share.data.first.interview, family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)
